#### ---

**Goal:**   
To learn how DoorDash users order family meals so we can offer better, more appealing group meal options. This includes improving pricing, how we present the product, and our marketing.

**Approach:**   
A survey of **505 DoorDash users** in multi-person households was conducted to study family meal ordering behaviors, including those who order family meals recently and those who do not. Sampling bias was corrected using rake weights for DashPass status, tenure, total orders, and NV orders in the L28D.

| ✨TL;DR:  We should prioritize solving for weekday dinner, where the need for convenience is strongest and volume is highest. Weekend dinners are treat occasions where families are willing to spend more i.e., this is a premium play, but secondary. Local restaurants hold a large share of family orders, but chains dominate the budget end, thus making local far less competitive for price-sensitive family meals. The unlock: Make "local \+ affordable" a reality, not a trade-off. Customization is a must-have: Families customize heavily. Mid-sized households of 3-4 frequently swap sides and adjust spice levels, and families with young kids prioritize keeping the meal balanced. Family bundles need to flex by age and allow easy swaps: As kids get older, families stop ordering ‘kid meals’ and start ordering adult entrees for teens.  Families prioritize value: affordable bundles and upfront pricing win across segments. 'Kids eat free' resonates strongly with families with young kids but less with teens who eat adult-sized meals. For households of 3-4 people, a family meal priced around $30 is seen as a bargain. However, families are typically paying $10–20 more than what they consider a fair price, highlighting a significant opportunity to adjust pricing. |
| :---- |

**Most families on DoorDash order monthly. But nearly three-quarters also order directly from restaurants, drawn by better deals and lower fees: 22% of 1P orders were under $30 vs. just 12% on DoorDash\!**

| ![][image2] | Monthly cadence: 61% of families order on DoorDash at least once or 2–3 times a month, making it a consistent part of their meal routine. High loyalty: Half of DoorDash family meal users don’t use other delivery apps at all. But dual behavior: 3 in 4 also order directly from restaurants. Reason for going direct: 60% cite better promotions and lower fees as their main reasons for skipping DoorDash. Based on users’ last family order, 22% of direct orders were under $30 vs. just 12% on DoorDash, a 10pp gap\! Q: In the last month, how often have you ordered a family meal from each of the following sources? (N \= 504\) |

**Local restaurants hold a large share of family orders, but chains dominate the budget end, thus making local far less competitive for price-sensitive family meals. The unlock: Make "local \+ affordable" a reality, not a trade-off.**

| ![][image5] | Chains lead the category: 51% of family orders come from chains, including 21% from fast food chain. **We should offer flexible meal formats from fully shared to fully individual to accommodate different family dynamics. This is especially important for families with teens who prefer individual control over their food choices.**

| ![][image6] | Family meals are split between “everyone gets their own” and “let’s share.” Household size drives format choices: Bigger families (5+) want family bundles while mid-size households (3-4) lean individual. The teen effect: Teens want their own food, not a shared pizza. Individual meal orders spike \+4 pp when teens are present, while shared pizza drops \-9 pp. But teens do like bundles (+8 pp): Unlike shared pizza where everyone eats the same thing, bundles let each person get something different. Q: What did you order for this family meal? Pick the closest match. (N= 478). Exclude 2% other. |
| :---: | :---- |

**Families customize heavily. Mid-sized households of 3-4 frequently swap sides and adjust spice levels, and families with young kids prioritize keeping the meal balanced.**

| ![][image7] | ![][image8] |
| :---- | :---- |
| Customization is very popular: 60% of the meals are customized in some way. Build-your-own option is popular across all household sizes and compositions, accounting for one in four meals. Medium-sized households (3-4 people) are more likely to swap out sides and modify spice levels.  Q: Did you customize any part of this meal for your household? (N \= 478\) | A little over half of all family meals are chosen with health considerations in mind. The most common healthy eating approach is trying to maintain a balanced mix of food types: one in five families aims for a balance of protein, vegetables, and carbs. Households with young children (under 12\) are more likely to prioritize health considerations than households without young children. Q: Thinking about that family meal, did you make any choices to make it feel healthier or more balanced for your household? (N \= 478\) |

**As kids get older, families stop ordering ‘kid meals’ and start ordering adult entrees for teens. Family bundles need to flex by age and allow easy swaps.**

| ![][image9] | Child age drives distinct ordering patterns. Families with young kids (0–12) lean toward kid-specific items, while teens default to full adult entrées i.e., teens eat like adults.  Across households, ordering separate items for kids (73%) far exceeds sharing (36%).  The opportunity: Kid-focused meals for younger families, adult-portion options for teens, and shareable bundles for the 36% who prefer to split dishes. Q: How did you handle meals for children (of any age) in your household? (N \= 283\) |

**Families prioritize value: affordable bundles and upfront pricing win across segments. 'Kids eat free' resonates strongly with families with young kids but less with teens who eat adult-sized meals.**

**For 3-4 person households, $30 is considered a bargain price for a family meal and feels compelling. On average, however, families are paying about $10–20 more than what they consider a fair price. This is an opportunity gap to close.**

| ![][image11] | The "deal" zone is $24–31, with around $30 being optimal for most families. This aligns with actual behavior with 40–45% of orders fall in the $30–50 range. Families feel they're overpaying. Almost half of the orders land in what customers perceive as "expensive" or "too expensive" ($50+), signaling dissatisfaction with current pricing. Unmet demand exists at $30. Only 8–16% of orders are under $30 today. A $30 family meal would feel like strong value vs. typical spend. The wide $18–20 gap between "deal" and "expensive" suggests weak price anchoring, leaving room for value-driven tiers without pricing out Cx. Convenience commands a premium over home cooking: Cx is willing to pay up to 50% more for delivery among smaller households, and about 20% for 5+ person families. Q: Still thinking about a typical weekday dinner for your household, at what total price (in US dollars) would you consider the total order to be (N \= 504\) |

Appendix:

Goal: 

* To understand how multi-person, “family” meal delivery and pickup orders fit into household routines i.e., who orders, for whom, how often, from where, why, and at what price points these meals are considered reasonable or too expensive.  
* We will ask users about *their most recent family meal*.  
* The outcomes of this survey will inform a follow-up concept test.

#### 

Target Audience & Sample Size: 

* Adults (18+) who live in multi-person households and are actively involved in deciding or sharing decisions about what to order for delivery or pickup meals for the family.   
* They must have recent experience ordering meals for multiple people via DoorDash, another delivery app, or directly from a restaurant within the past month.  
* Target sample size: 400 \- 600\.
